\begin_layout Section
The model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our approach is to develop an evolutionary demographic model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hamilton1964a,Taylor1996,Rousset2004,Taylor2007,Lion2011,Lehmann2014"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 of the evolution of genomic imprinting on age at sexual maturation.
 Consider a population distributed over infinitely many territories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wright1931,Wright1951"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, in which individuals reproduce sexually and generations are nonoverlapping.
 Each territory contains 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{f}}$
\end_inset

 adult female breeders and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{m}}$
\end_inset

 adult male breeders.
 Territories are linked by juvenile dispersal, so that newborn females (or
 males) disperse to random territory with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

) and remain on their natal patch with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{f}}=1-d_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{m}}=1-d_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to seminal models (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Roff1984,Stearns1986"
literal "true"

\end_inset

), we assume that there is a trade-off between survival as an offspring
 and reproductive success as an adult, mediated by age at maturity, which
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 in females and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 in males.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Say why we consider sex-limited expression of age at maturity
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Although qualitatively similar, the trade-off takes a slightly different
 form dependent on the sex considered: in adult females, age at maturity
 directly affects the number of offspring produced, while in adult males
 age at maturity determines his fertilization success relative to other
 males.
 Consequently, females provide all investment in offspring, while males
 compete for paternity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will write 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a)$
\end_inset

 for a female's fecundity or a male's relative success in competition for
 paternity, where we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a)$
\end_inset

 increases deceleratingly with 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 At the start of each generation, a focal female of age 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}^{i}$
\end_inset

 then produces a large number of offspring (in a 1:1 sex ratio) proportional
 to her fecundity 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{i})$
\end_inset

, while the average fecundity in the local patch is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

.
 A focal male's share of fertilizations of all locally born young is then
 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{f}}/n_{\mathrm{m}}\times f(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{i})/f(a_{\mathrm{m}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{f}}/n_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 reflects the average number of matings achieved by a single male, while
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{i})/f(a_{\mathrm{m}})$
\end_inset

 reflects his fertilization success relative to the average fertilization
 success by all males in the local patch.
 Upon birth, female and male offspring survive with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $s(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s(a_{\mathrm{m}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 strictly decreases with increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Female and male offspring who survive to maturity then disperse with respective
 probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

, after which native and immigrant female and male offspring on each patch
 compete for the 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 breeding positions vacated by the death of the previous generation.
 Offspring who fail to claim a breeding position die, after which the life
 cycle repeats itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that the evolution of age at maturity proceeds through the successive
 substitution of mutations of small effect 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Geritz1998,Rousset2004,McGill2007"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and selection gradients describing the evolutionary dynamics of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 in the Online Supplement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Result 1: age at maturity increases with philopatry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fix ideas, we first consider a scenario in which individuals express
 their own phenotype, in the absence of imprinting or parental effects.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ES_nf2_nm2"

\end_inset

 then shows how sex-biased dispersal influences optimal age at maturity
 in females (panels A, C) and males (panels B, D) for different probabilities
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 with which males exlusively mate within their their local group.
 Importantly, when males mate only locally 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ell=1)$
\end_inset

, we find that sex-differences in dispersal only affects age at maturity
 in females but not males: specifically, female age at maturity increases
 with rising levels of female philopatry (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ES_nf2_nm2"

\end_inset

A), whereas male age at maturity is unaffected by dispersal (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ES_nf2_nm2"

\end_inset

B).
 By contrast, when males mate nonlocally, we find a qualitatively similar
 pattern in both sexes: age at maturity increases with the probability of
 philopatry of that sex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why do we find these patterns? Regarding female age maturity, consider a
 case where females are more philopatric than males.
 In this case, any increase in female fecundity 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

 (through a delayed female age at maturity) will increase the number of
 philopatric daughters competing in the local patch.
 At the same time however, increased 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

 also results in a larger number of dispersing sons, who will be likely
 to compete with unrelated males in a remote patch.
 By contrast, any increases in female juvenile survival 
\begin_inset Formula $s(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

 only increases local competition among juvenile females, with no concomitant
 effect on male relatives.
 Consequently, the prospect of producing dispersing sons leads females to
 value fecundity more strongly than survival, favoring an increased female
 age at maturity with increasing female philopatry.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regarding male age at maturity, consider a scenario where males are dispersing
 sex: any increase in male fertility 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{m}})$
\end_inset

 (through a later male age at maturity) increases local competition for
 sirings among adult males (rather than among young).
 Similarly, any increase in male juvenile survival 
\begin_inset Formula $s(a_{\mathrm{m}})$
\end_inset

 also increases competition among male juvenile relatives.
 Indeed, it can be shown that male philopatry increases local competition
 among juvenile males and adult males at exactly the same rate.
 Consequently, we recover the classical result by Taylor 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Taylor1992"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 that limited dispersal has no effect on social interactionsw
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
 In the presence of nonlocal mating, however, adult males are now more likely
 to compete for fertilizations with unrelated males, causing males to value
 fertility more strongly than survival and favoring an increased male age
 at maturity with increasing male philopatry.
\end_layout

