\end_inset

 reflects the probability that an allele in offspring of sex 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is inherited from a parent of sex 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 In diploids, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{ij}=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 In haplodiploids, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\mathrm{ff}}=1/2,\ t_{\mathrm{fm}}=1,\ t_{\mathrm{fm}}=1/2,t_{\mathrm{mm}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The first part within brackets reflect the proportion of daughters who
 remain in the natal patch (with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-d_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

) and successfully survive with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $s(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{j}i})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{j}i}$
\end_inset

 reflects the phenotype of the focal allele in juveniles.
 These philopatric daughters compete for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 breeding positions with all 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{f}}f(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{ff}})(1-d_{\mathrm{f}})s(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{jff}})$
\end_inset

 surviving philopatric female juveniles and all 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{f}}f(a_{\mathrm{f}})d_{\mathrm{f}}s(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

 surviving immigrant female juveniles.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{ff}})$
\end_inset

 reflects the fecundity averaged over all adult females in the local patch
 when the focal allele copy is borne by an adult female, while 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

 reflects the average fecundity of adult females in the rest of the population.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $s(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{jff}})$
\end_inset

 reflects the average survival of all female juveniles produced in the local
 patch when the focal allele copy is borne by an adult female and the survival
 
\begin_inset Formula $s(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

 of female juveniles in the rest of the population.
 Alternatively, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, a surviving daughter migrates to a random remote patch, where she competes
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-d_{\mathrm{f}}+d_{\mathrm{f}})f(a_{\mathrm{f}})s(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

 surviving female juveniles for breeding positions.
 The other equations can be derived in a similar fashion.
 When considering the number 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\cdot\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 of successfully established offspring born from a focal adult male, note
 that he can compete for matings in the local patch with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

, while he mates in a random remote patch with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\ell$
\end_inset

.
 In both cases, his average mating success is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{f}}f(a_{\mathrm{m}})/(n_{\mathrm{m}}f(a_{\mathrm{m}}))$
\end_inset

, and the number of offspring he sires is given by the average fecundity
 of the female breeders in that patch (
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{fm}})$
\end_inset

 in the local patch, indicating female fecundity when the focal allele copy
 is present in a male) or 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a_{\mathrm{f}})$
\end_inset

 elsewhere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fitness expressions male age at maturity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
w_{\mathrm{ff}} & =\frac{1}{2}t_{\mathrm{ff}}\label{eq:am:wff}\\
w_{\mathrm{mf}} & =\frac{1}{2}t_{\mathrm{mf}}\left[\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}\left(1-d_{\mathrm{m}}\right)s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{j}i}\right)}{n_{\mathrm{f}}\left[\left(1-d_{\mathrm{m}}\right)s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{jmf}}\right)+d_{\mathrm{m}}s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}\right)\right]}+\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}d_{\mathrm{m}}s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{j}i}\right)}{n_{\mathrm{f}}s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}\right)}\right]\label{eq:am:wmf}\\
w_{\mathrm{fm}} & =\frac{1}{2}t_{\mathrm{fm}}\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left[\ell\frac{f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{i}\right)}{\ell f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{mm}}\right)+\left(1-\ell\right)f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}\right)}+\left(1-\ell\right)\frac{f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{i}\right)}{f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}\right)}\right]\label{eq:am:wfm}\\
w_{\mathrm{mm}} & =\frac{1}{2}t_{\mathrm{mm}}\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left\{ \ell\frac{f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{i}\right)}{\ell f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{mm}}\right)+\left(1-\ell\right)f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}\right)}\left[\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}\left(1-d_{\mathrm{m}}\right)s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{j}i}\right)}{n_{\mathrm{f}}\left[\left(1-d_{\mathrm{m}}\right)s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{jmm}}\right)+d_{\mathrm{m}}s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}\right)\right]}+\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}d_{\mathrm{m}}s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{j}i}\right)}{n_{\mathrm{f}}s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}\right)}\right]\right..\label{eq:am:wmm}\\
 & \left.+\left(1-\ell\right)\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{i}\right)s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{j}i,\text{nonloc}}\right)}{n_{\mathrm{f}}f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}\right)s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}\right)}\right\} \nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Selection gradients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Expressions for female and male fitnesses are then given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w_{\mathrm{f}} & =\frac{v_{\mathrm{m}}}{v_{\mathrm{f}}}w_{\mathrm{mf}}+w_{\mathrm{ff}}\\
w_{\mathrm{m}} & =\frac{v_{\mathrm{f}}}{v_{\mathrm{m}}}w_{\mathrm{fm}}+w_{\mathrm{mm}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We then derive selection gradients that determine the rate of evolutionary
 change in 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 using a direct fitness approach (also called neighbour-modulated fitness)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hamilton1964a,Taylor1996,Rousset2004,Taylor2007"
literal "true"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\mathrm{d}w}{\mathrm{d}a_{\mathrm{f}}} & =\left.c_{\mathrm{f}}\left(\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{f}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{f}}^{i}}r_{\mathrm{m}i}+\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{f}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{j}i}}r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}+\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{f}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{ff}}}r_{\mathrm{f\rightarrow f}}+\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{f}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{jff}}}r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{fjuv}}\right)\right|_{a_{\mathrm{f}}^{x}=a_{\mathrm{f}}}\nonumber \\
 & +\left.c_{\mathrm{m}}\left(\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{m}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{j}i}}r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}+\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{m}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{j}i,\text{nonloc}}}r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own nonloc juv},\mathrm{f}}+\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{m}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{fm}}}r_{\mathrm{m\rightarrow f}}+\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{m}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{jfm}}}r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{fjuv}}\right)\right|_{a_{\mathrm{f}}^{x}=a_{\mathrm{f}}}\label{eq:selgrad:af}\\
\frac{\mathrm{d}w}{\mathrm{d}a_{\mathrm{m}}} & =\left.c_{\mathrm{f}}\left(\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{f}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{j}i}}r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}+\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{f}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{jmf}}}r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{mjuv}}\right)\right|_{a_{\mathrm{m}}^{x}=a_{\mathrm{m}}}\nonumber \\
 & +c_{\mathrm{m}}\left(\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{m}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{m}}^{i}}r_{\mathrm{m}i}+\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{m}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{j}i}}r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}+\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{m}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{j}i}}r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own nonloc juv},\mathrm{m}}+\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{m}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{mm}}}r_{\mathrm{m\rightarrow m}}\right.\nonumber \\
 & \phantom{c_{\mathrm{m}}c_{\mathrm{m}}1}+\left.\left.\frac{\partial w_{\mathrm{f}}}{\partial a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{jmm}}}r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{mjuv}}\right)\right|_{a_{\mathrm{m}}^{x}=a_{\mathrm{m}}},\label{eq:selgrad:am}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}i}$
\end_inset

 indicates relatedness between the adult bearer of the focal allele and
 itself, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 reflects relatedness between an adult female and one of her daughters,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 reflects relatedness between two adult females sampled randomly with replacemen
t from the same patch, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{fjuv}}$
\end_inset

 the relatedness between an adult female and a locally born juvenile female
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 reflects relatedness between an adult male and one of his daughters.
 All partial derivatives of the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}^{x}=[a_{\mathrm{f}}^{i},a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{j}i},\ldots,a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{jfm}}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{m}}^{x}=[a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{j}i},a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{jmf}}\ldots,a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{jmm}}]$
\end_inset

 are evaluated at the resident trait values 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Evolutionarily singular strategies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fix ideas, we first assess a `baseline' scenario in which populations
 are well mixed (full female and male dispersal: 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{f}}=0,\ h_{\mathrm{m}}=0$
\end_inset

).
 We then recover the classical result 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Roff2002"
literal "true"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-\frac{s^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}{s\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)} & =\frac{f^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}{f\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}\label{eq:well_mixed:af:ES}\\
-\frac{s^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star}\right)}{s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star}\right)} & =\frac{f^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star}\right)}{f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star}\right)},\label{eq:well_mixed:am:ES}
\end{align}

\end_inset

implying that the marginal decrease in juvenile survival 
\begin_inset Formula $s(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 (caused by a slightly higher age at maturity) must precisely balance the
 proportional increase in adult fecundity 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\cdot).$
\end_inset

 However, as noted before 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Johnstone2014"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, this result changes in a viscous population, where we find:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-\frac{1}{2}\left(r_{\text{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow self,juv}}-r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{competing juv}}\right)\frac{s^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}{s\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)} & =\left(r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own young}}-r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{competing young}}\right)\frac{f^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}{f\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}\label{eq:viscous:af:ES}\\
-\frac{1}{2}\left(r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{self,juv}}-r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{competing juv}}\right)\frac{s^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star}\right)}{s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star}\right)} & =\left(r_{\mathrm{self}}-r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{competing young}}\right)\frac{f^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star}\right)}{f\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star}\right)}.\label{eq:viscous:am:ES}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Female age at maturity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}w/\mathrm{d}a_{\mathrm{f}}=0$
\end_inset

, we obtain the following identity for the singular strategy 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star})$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-\frac{1}{2}\left[r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}+r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}-h_{\mathrm{f}}^{2}\left(r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{fjuv}}+\ell r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{fjuv}}\right)\right]\frac{s^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}{s\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)} & =\nonumber \\
\left[r_{\mathrm{f}}^{i}+\ell r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}-\frac{1}{2}\left(h_{\mathrm{f}}^{2}+h_{\mathrm{m}}^{2}\right)\left(r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}+r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}\right)\right]\frac{f^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}{f\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}\label{eq:supplement:af_ES}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Now we substitute on the first line in the equation above for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{self juv}} & =r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}+r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}\label{eq:supplement:ES:rfselfjuv}\\
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{competing juv,f}} & =h_{\mathrm{f}}^{2}\left(r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{fjuv}}+\ell r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{fjuv}}\right),\label{eq:supplement:ES:rfcompetingjuv}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the first line reflects relatedness of the focal allele to itself
 when present in a female juvenile.
 The second line reflects relatedness of the focal allele to other, competing
 female juveniles.
 On the right-hand side, we substitute for
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own offspring}} & =r_{\mathrm{f}}^{i}+\ell r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}\label{eq:supplement:ES:rfownoffspring}\\
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{competing offspring}} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(h_{\mathrm{f}}^{2}+h_{\mathrm{m}}^{2}\right)\left(r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}+\ell r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}\right),\label{eq:supplement:ES:rfcompetingoffspring}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the first line gives relatedness to an adult female's own offspring
 (male and female), as a result of the direct transmission of her own allele
 copies to her offspring (
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}}^{i}$
\end_inset

) and the transmission of identical allele copies to her offspring via her
 locally mating partner, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 The second line gives relatedness to offspring that compete with the adult
 female's own offspring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Male age at maturity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}w/\mathrm{d}a_{\mathrm{m}}=0$
\end_inset

, we obtain the following identity for the singular strategy 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star})$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-\frac{1}{2}\left[r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}+r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}-h_{\mathrm{m}}^{2}\left(r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{mjuv}}+\ell r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{mjuv}}\right)\right]\frac{s^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star}\right)}{s\left(a_{\mathrm{m}}^{\star}\right)} & =\nonumber \\
\left[r_{\mathrm{m}}^{i}-\ell r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}\right]\frac{f^{\prime}\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}{f\left(a_{\mathrm{f}}^{\star}\right)}\label{eq:supplement:am_ES}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Now we substitute on the left-hand side of the equation above for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{self juv}} & =r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}+r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}\label{eq:supplement:ES:rmselfjuv}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{competing juv,m}} & =h_{\mathrm{m}}^{2}\left(r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{mjuv}}+\ell r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{mjuv}}\right),\label{eq:supplement:ES:rmcompetingjuv}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the first line reflects relatedness of the focal allele to itself
 when present in a male juvenile.
 The second line reflects relatedness of the focal allele to other, competing
 male juveniles.
 On the right-hand side, we substitute for
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own offspring}} & =r_{\mathrm{m}}^{i}+\ell r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}\label{eq:supplement:ES:rmownoffspring}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{competing offspring}} & =\ell\left(r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}+r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}\right).\label{eq:supplement:ES:rmcompetingoffspring}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the first line gives relatedness to an adult male's own offspring
 (male and female), as a result of the direct transmission of her own allele
 copies to her offspring (
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{m}}^{i}$
\end_inset

) and the transmission of identical allele copies to her offspring via his
 related partner (when mating locally): 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

.
 The second line gives relatedness to offspring that compete with the adult
 female's own offspring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Relatedness coefficients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Diplodiploidy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coefficients of consanguinity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficient of consanguinity 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 between two randomly sampled allele copies in the same female or male individua
l is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wright1922"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Q_{\mathrm{f}} & =Q_{\mathrm{m}}=\frac{1}{2}\left(1+\ell Q_{\mathrm{fm}}\right),\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:Qf}
\end{align}

\end_inset

as with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 we sample the same allele copy so that the probability of identity is equal
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, whereas with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 the other allele copy is sampled.
 The latter allele copy is identical to the former when both individual's
 parents share the same allele copy with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, it is required that the individual's father has mated in the
 local patch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

 we need to derive expressions for the coefficients of consanguinity between
 two distinct juveniles 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{xy}^{\mathrm{j}}$
\end_inset

, one of sex 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and the other of sex 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 before dispersal:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Q_{\mathrm{ff}}^{\mathrm{j}} & =Q_{\mathrm{fm}}^{\mathrm{j}}=Q_{\mathrm{mf}}^{\mathrm{j}}=Q_{\mathrm{mm}}^{\mathrm{j}}=\frac{1}{4}\left(\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}Q_{\mathrm{f}}+\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}Q_{\mathrm{ff}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\ell Q_{\mathrm{fm}}+\frac{1}{4}\ell^{2}\left(\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}Q_{\mathrm{m}}+\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}Q_{\mathrm{mm}}\right),\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:QffJ}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the first part on the right hand side reflects the probability that
 in both juveniles, maternally inherited alleles are sampled (probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $1/4$
\end_inset

).
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, these alleles descend from the same mother (hence identity is given by
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

), whereas with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{f}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, alleles are inherited from different mothers, which share the same allele
 copy with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathrm{ff}}$
\end_inset

.
 The second part on the right hand side reflects the probability that we
 sample one maternally inherited allele copy in one juvenile and a paternally
 inherited allele copy in another (with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

).
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

, the paternally inherited allele is inherited from a local male.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

, the maternally inherited and paternally inherited copies are then identical.
 The last part reflects the probability that two paternally inherited allele
 copies are sampled in juveniles (with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/4$
\end_inset

), where the probability that both juveniles have been sired by locally
 breeding males is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then have the following coefficients of consanguinity in adults
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Q_{\mathrm{ff}} & =h_{\mathrm{f}}^{2}Q_{\mathrm{ff}}^{\mathrm{j}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:Qff}\\
Q_{\mathrm{fm}} & =Q_{\mathrm{mf}}=h_{\mathrm{f}}h_{\mathrm{m}}Q_{\mathrm{fm}}^{\mathrm{j}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:Qfm}\\
Q_{\mathrm{mm}} & =h_{\mathrm{m}}^{2}Q_{\mathrm{mm}}^{\mathrm{j}},\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:Qmm}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{f}}=1-d_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{m}}=1-d_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 are the probabilities juvenile females and males stay in their natal patch.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

 reflects the coefficient of consanguinity between an adult female and male
 that are randomly sampled in the local patch.
 Equilibrium coefficients of consanguinity (denoted by hats: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\cdot}$
\end_inset

) are then obtained from solving the above recursions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Relatedness - diploid, autosomal inheritance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{m}i}$
\end_inset

 in eqns.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:selgrad:af"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:selgrad:af"

\end_inset

) denote relatedness between the focal bearer and itself:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}i} & =\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}},\ r_{\mathrm{m}i}=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}.\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:ri}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Throughout, relatedness coefficients reflect the phenotypic regression of
 the mutant's phenotype on the focal's additive genetic value 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hamilton1970,Gardner2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality, we assume that the mutant allele has phenotype
 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 while the resident allele has phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 One of the two alleles of the focal breeder is certain to be a mutant allele.
 However, when when both the focal's parents bear the mutant allele, which
 occurs with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

 times by the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 that the focal's father sires offspring in its local patch, the other allele
 is a mutant allele as well.
 We then have 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}i}=r_{\mathrm{m}i}=\frac{1}{2}\cdot1+\frac{1}{2}\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\cdot1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 reflect identity between a focal female's own daughters and sons, given
 that these daughters and sons bear the mutant allele copy (as we obviously
 consider the expected number of 
