status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{mutant}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 offspring in eqns.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:af:wff"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:am:wmm"

\end_inset

).
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 reflect identity between a focal male's own daughters and sons who bear
 the mutant allele copy.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}},\ r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own\ juv},\mathrm{m}}=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rownjuvF}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}} & =\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}},\ r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own\ juv},\mathrm{m}}=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}.\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rownjuvM}
\end{align}

\end_inset

These focal sons and daughters bear at least one mutant allele (with phenotype
 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

) with certainty, so the share of this allele in the phenotype is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\cdot1$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, the other allele is also a mutant when both parents share
 identical alleles, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
 When the bearer of the focal allele copy is a female (first line in the
 equation above), sharing of identical alleles between parents only occurs
 when her offspring are sired by a local male, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 When the bearer of the focal allele copy is male (second line), sharing
 of alleles between parents is independent of local mating, as fitness equations
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:af:wfm"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:af:wmm"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:am:wfm"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:am:wmm"

\end_inset

) are already conditional upon focal males mating locally (see below for
 relatedness coefficients corresponding to nonlocally mating males).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients between the focal male's allele copy and its remotely
 sired daughters and sons (who necessarily bear a mutant allele copy, again
 since eqns.
 [
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:af:wff"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:am:wmm"

\end_inset

] reflect mutant fitness) are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own nonlocal juv},\mathrm{f}} & =\frac{1}{2},\ r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own nonloc juv},\mathrm{f}}=\frac{1}{2},\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rnonlocaljuv}
\end{align}

\end_inset

as these offspring are certain to bear the father's mutant allele copy (with
 phenotypic share 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\cdot1$
\end_inset

), while the other allele copy is inherited from an unrelated mother in
 a nonlocal patch
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients between alleles in a randomly sampled adult breeder
 (female and male respectively) and the focal adult male breeder (i.e., sampling
 with replacement) are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}} & =\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rf->f}\\
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rf->m}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{mf}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rm->f}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}} & =\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{mm}}.\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rm->m}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Regarding the first line, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, the same adult female is sampled, so the phenotypic  regression is similar
 to that in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:relatedness:diploid:ri"

\end_inset

), namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{f}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, however, two distinct adult females are sampled.
 The probability that the nonfocal female bears the mutant allele is then
 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}$
\end_inset

.
 The other relatedness coeffcients can be derived in the same fashion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients between alleles in a randomly sampled juvenile
 breeder (female and male respectively and not necessarily bearing a mutant
 allele copy) and the focal adult female breeder are given bt
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvf}} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rfjuvf}\\
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvm}} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right).\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rfjuvm}
\end{align}

\end_inset

With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, a juvenile is sampled whose mother is the focal adult female.
 The maternally inherited allele copy's share in determining the offspring's
 phenotype is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 and the probability that the actual mutant allele is inherited from the
 focal mother to her offspring is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

.
 The share of the paternally inherited allele in the offspring's phenotype
 is again 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 and the probability that it is, again, a mutant allele is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{f}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 the juvenile has a different mother than the focal: the maternally inherited
 allele copy is mutant with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}$
\end_inset

, and its paternally inherited allele copy is mutant with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients between alleles in a randomly sampled juvenile
 breeder (female and male respectively and not necessarily bearing a mutant
 allele copy) and the focal adult male breeder are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvf}} & =\frac{1}{2}\ell\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left(\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{mm}}+Q_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rmjuvf}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvm}} & =\frac{1}{2}\ell\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left(\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{mm}}+Q_{\mathrm{fm}}\right),\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:rmjuvm}
\end{align}

\end_inset

the derivation of which is similar to that of eqns.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:relatedness:diploid:rfjuvf"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:relatedness:diploid:rfjuvm"

\end_inset

) with the difference that relatedness between local juveniles sired by
 the focal and the focal itself (first part in the equations above) is condition
al upon the focal male mating locally with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 When the local juveniles are sired by father different to the focal (second
 part), the focal male shares allele copies with the juvenile's mother with
 probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

 regardless of whether the focal itself mates locally or nonlocally.
 However, the focal male only shares allele copies with the juvenile's father
 (with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{mm}}$
\end_inset

) when that father mates locally with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Relatedness - maternal expression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The phenotype of a focal adult female and male is now determined by their
 mothers.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}i}^{\mathrm{M}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{m}i}^{\mathrm{M}}$
\end_inset

 denote relatedness between the focal and itself, where the superscript
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{M}$
\end_inset

 denotes that the phenotype is expressed by their mothers.
 We now have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}i}^{\mathrm{M}} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right),\ r_{\mathrm{m}i}^{\mathrm{M}}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right).\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:ri}
\end{align}

\end_inset

With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 the focal's mother first gene copy is a mutant gene copy (as with probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

, the focal received its mutant allele copy from the mother, or alternatively
 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 received a copy from the focal's father which is identicaly by descent
 to alleles present in the focal's mother with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

, giving 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
 The first gene copy in the focal's mother thus contributes 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\cdot1$
\end_inset

 towards the total phenotype.
 The focal's mother second gene copy is also a mutant version in case it
 is identical by descent to her mutant allele copy in the first position,
 which occurs with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

, again resulting in a contribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\cdot1$
\end_inset

 towards the total phenotype.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness between a focal adult female (or male) and their own locally
 sired offspring in case of maternal expression is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{M}}=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rfownjuvf}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{M}}=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}.\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rmownjuvf}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Regarding the first line, we need to consider relatedness between the focal
 mother and herself, as she expresses the phenotype of her offspring.
 The focal's first gene copy is by definition the mutant copy, contributing
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\cdot1$
\end_inset

 to the total focal's phenotype.
 Her second gene copy is also a mutant copy in case it is identical by descent
 to the first gene copy, which occurs with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

, in this case resulting in a contribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\cdot1$
\end_inset

 to the focal's phenotype.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\cdot1+\frac{1}{2}\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\cdot1=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

.
 In case of maternal expression, relatedness between a focal male and its
 own offspring actually is reflected by relatedness between a focal male
 and the mother of its own offspring, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients between alleles sampled in a focal male's remotely
 sired daughters and sons (who express the focal phenotype), when the focal
 allele is borne by the focal father, are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own nonlocal juv},\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =0,\ r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own nonloc juv},\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{M}}=0.\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rnonlocaljuv}
\end{align}

\end_inset

as a focal male's offspring's phenotypes are expressed by a remotely sired
 – and hence unrelated – mother.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients between a focal adult female and any randomly sampled
 adult female (sampled with replacement) when phenotypes are maternally
 expressed are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}h_{\mathrm{f}}^{2}\left[\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\right]\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rf->f}\\
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =\frac{1}{2}h_{\mathrm{f}}h_{\mathrm{m}}\left[\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\right]\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rf->m}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =\frac{1}{2}h_{\mathrm{m}}h_{\mathrm{f}}\left[\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\right]\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rm->f}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}h_{\mathrm{m}}^{2}\left[\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\right].\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rm->m}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Regarding the first line, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, the focal adult female is again resampled, so relatedness is given by
 eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:ri"

\end_inset

).
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{f}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, however, an adult female distinct from the focal is sampled.
 Both the focal and the other female are born in the local patch with probabilit
y 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{f}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 they share the same mother, so the probability of identity is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}})$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{f}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, the other individual has a distinc mother, so the probability of identity
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}})$
\end_inset

: with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

, the focal allele is maternally inherited, so identity betweeen this allele
 and the allele in the nonfocal mother is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, the focal allele is paternally inherited from a locally
 mating male with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/2)\ell$
\end_inset

, so that the probability of identity is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regarding the second line, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{f}}h_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 both the focal adult female and the sampled adult male are born in the
 local patch (rather than unrelated immigrants).
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, the adult male shares the same mother with the focal female, so relatedness
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}})$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{f}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, the randomly sampled adult male has a different mother as the focal, so
 identity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}})$
\end_inset

.
 The third line can be derived in the same fashion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regarding the last line, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

, the randomly sampled adult male is identical to the focal male adult,
 so the probability of identity is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}})$
\end_inset

.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{m}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

, an adult male distinct from the focal is sampled, and with probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{m}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 both adult males are born in the local patch, in which case they either
 share the same mother or have different mothers, similar to what has been
 derived before.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{juv}x}^{\mathrm{M}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{juv}x}^{\mathrm{M}}$
\end_inset

 between the focal allele in an adult female or male and any locally born
 juvenile of sex 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (bearing the mutant allele or not) in the case of maternal expression are
 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvf}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rfjuvf}\\
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvm}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rfjuvm}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvf}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rmjuvf}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvm}}^{\mathrm{M}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}.\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rmjuvm}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Regarding the first line, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 a juvenile is sampled whose mother is the focal adult female.
 Hence, relatedness is then the same as eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:relatedness:diploid:MC:rfownjuvf"

\end_inset

).
 Alternatively, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{f}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 a juvenile with a distinct mother is sampled.
 As we consider maternal control, relatedness is that between the focal
 adult female and another adult female in the local patch 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}$
\end_inset

.
 Regarding the third line, relatedness is that between a focal adult male
 and the mother of any locally born juvenile, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
 Local mating plays no role, as the focal male does not need to have sired
 the offspring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Relatedness - paternal expression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The phenotype of a focal adult female and male is now determined by their
 father.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}i}^{\mathrm{P}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{m}i}^{\mathrm{P}}$
\end_inset

 denote relatedness between the focal and itself, where the superscript
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{P}$
\end_inset

 denotes that the phenotype is paternally expressed.
 We now have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}i}^{\mathrm{P}} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right),\ r_{\mathrm{m}i}^{\mathrm{P}}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right).\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:PC:ri}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Relatedness between a focal adult female (or male) and their own offspring
 in case of paternal expression is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{P}} & =r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{P}}=\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:PC:rfownjuvf}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{P}} & =r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{P}}=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}.\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:PC:rmownjuvf}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Relatedness between a focal adult male and his own remotely sired offspring
 in case of paternal expression is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own nonlocal juv},\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{P}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}},\ r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own nonloc juv},\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{P}}=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}.\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:PC:rnonlocaljuv}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Relatedness coefficients between a focal adult female and any randomly sampled
 adult female (sampled with replacement) when phenotypes are paternally
 expressed are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{P}} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}h_{\mathrm{f}}^{2}\left[\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\ell\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\ell\left(\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{mm}}+\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\right]\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:PC:rf-f}\\
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{P}} & =r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{P}}=\frac{1}{2}h_{\mathrm{f}}h_{\mathrm{m}}\left[\ell\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\ell\left(\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{mm}}+\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\right]\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:PC:rm->f}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{P}} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}h_{\mathrm{f}}^{2}\left[\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\ell\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\ell\left(\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{mm}}+\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\right]\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:PC:rm->m}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Regarding 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{P}}$
\end_inset

, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, the focal adult female is resampled, so that relatedness of the focal
 to her own father is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/2)(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}})$
\end_inset

 as in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:relatedness:diploid:PC:ri"

\end_inset

).
 Alternatively, a different adult female is sampled with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{f}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, and both females are born in the natal patch with probabilty 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{f}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In that case, both females have the same locally mating father with probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell/n_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, the first allele copy in the focal female's father is identical to the
 mutant allele copy in the focal adult female, adding 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2\cdot1$
\end_inset

 to the father's total phenotype.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

 the second allele copy in the focal's father is identical to the first
 allele copy, as both the father's parents shared alleles with probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

