\begin_layout Subsubsection
Maternally inherited alleles expressed in offspring (imprinting)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote relatedness between a phenotype caused by a maternally inherited
 allele (MI) in the actor and a focal allele in the recipient by the superscript
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{MI}$
\end_inset

.
 We then have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{i\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}},\ r_{i\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{MI}}=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}},\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:ri}
\end{align}

\end_inset

as the identity between the maternally inherited allele and the focal allele
 is identical to the within-individual relatedness coefficient for each
 sex.
 Similarly, relatedness coefficients between a maternally-inherited allele
 from a focal's own daughters ('own juv,f') and sons ('own juv,m') (who
 express the focal phenotype) when the focal allele is borne by the mother
 and father respectively, are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =1,\ r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\text{own\ juv},\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{MI}}=1\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rownjuvF}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own juv},\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}},\ r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\text{own\ juv},\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{MI}}=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}.\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rownjuvM}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Regarding the first line, relatedness coefficients are 1 as a maternally
 inherited allele that causes a mutant phenotype can only be the mutant
 focal allele.
 Regarding the second line, alleles in a focal adult male are identical
 to maternally inherited alleles in his kids when alleles in his partner
 are identical to his own, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the probability of local mating 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 do not explicitly occur in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rownjuvM"

\end_inset

), as in case of maternal inheritance one samples alleles of two adult local
 breeders (male and female), rather than between father and offspring (in
 which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 matters).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients between the focal adult female (male) breeder and
 a maternally-inherited allele in a randomly sampled adult breeder (female
 and male respectively, sampled with replacement) and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(1+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rf->f}\\
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rf->m}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rm->f}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left(1+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right)++\frac{1}{2}\frac{n_{\mathrm{m}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{m}}}\left(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\right).\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rm->m}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Regarding the first line, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, we sample the same focal adult female again.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 we sample the maternally inherited allele in the focal recipient, which
 is identical to the MI-allele in the actor with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, we sample the paternally inherited allele in the recipient,
 so that identity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{f}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 the randomly sampled adult female is distinct from the focal so that relatednes
s of the focal's maternally and paternally inherited allele to the actors
 MI-allele is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/2)(\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}+\ell\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}})$
\end_inset

.
 Regarding the second line, the randomly sampled adult male is necessarily
 distinct from the focal adult female.
 Consequently, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, they share the same mother.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 the maternally inherited allele is sampled in the focal, which is identical
 to the maternally inherited allele in the sampled adult male actor with
 probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

, the paternally inherited allele is sampled in the focal, which is identical
 to maternally inherited allele in the sampled adult male actor with probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell Q_{\mathrm{fm}}$
\end_inset

.
 The remainder can be derived in a similar fashion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients between a maternally-inherited allele in a randomly
 sampled adult breeder (female and male respectively) and the focal adult
 male breeder are given bywhich can be derived in the same way as previously.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients between the focal adult female breeder an a maternally-
inherited allele in a randomly sampled juvenile breeder (female and male
 respectively) are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvf}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rfjuvf}\\
r_{\mathrm{f}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvm}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =\frac{1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}+\frac{n_{\mathrm{f}}-1}{n_{\mathrm{f}}}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}},\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rfjuvm}
\end{align}

\end_inset

as a maternally inherited allele in a juvenile stems directly from the focal
 adult female breeder with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

 so that identity is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, the maternally inherited allele stems from another local adult
 female breeder with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(n_{\mathrm{f}}-1)/n_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

, so that identity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ff}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedness coefficients between a maternally-inherited allele in a randomly
 sampled juvenile breeder (female and male respectively) and the focal adult
 male breeder are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvf}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}}\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rmjuvf}\\
r_{\mathrm{m}\rightarrow\mathrm{juvm}}^{\mathrm{MI}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{fm}},\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:MI:rmjuvm}
\end{align}

\end_inset

reflecting the identity of the focal allele in the adult male recipient
 and alleles present in the mother (which necessarily will be inherited
 to her offspring).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Paternally inherited alleles expressed in offspring (imprinting)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote relatedness of paternally inherited alleles by the superscript
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{PI}$
\end_inset

.
 We then have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{i\mathrm{f}}^{\mathrm{PI}} & =\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{f}},\ r_{i\mathrm{m}}^{\mathrm{PI}}=\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{m}},\label{eq:relatedness:diploid:PI:ri}
\end{align}

\end_inset

as we are interested in the relatedness between a focal gene copy (present
